ultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Telegram/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Telegram%201920%20May-%20Jun%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Telegram%201920%20May-%20Jun%20Grayscale%20-%200037.pdf }} }}\n\n{{refn|name=bentinck1980|{{cite book |author = William Bentinck-Smith |publisher = Harvard College Library |title = \"... a Memorial to My Dear Son\": Some Reflections on 65 Years of the Harry Elkins Widener Memorial Library |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=rLWxGQAACAAJ |year = 1980 }} }}\n\n{{refn|name=trib| {{citation |work = New York Tribune |date = May 1, 1920 |page = 7 |title = Explorers Kill Cannibals \u2013 Former Mrs. Widener Shares Perils in South America |url = http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1920-05-01/ed-1/seq-7/ }} }}\n\n{{refn| name=bring_back | {{citation |title=Harvard, Bring Back Geography! |first=Edward |last=Tenner|work=Harvard Magazine| date= May{{ndash}}June 1988}} }}\n\n{{refn|name=3rd_report|{{citation |<!--bibl info per http://hollis.harvard.edu/?itemid=|library/m/aleph|010521627-->\n| page=334\u20135 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nsgnAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA334 | year =1913\n|  work = Third report{{nbsp}}/ Harvard College Class of 1907.\n| author = Harvard College (1780- ). Class of 1907 | title=Harry Elkins Widener\n| location = New York | publisher = Press of Styles and Cash\n}} }}\n\n{{refn|name=senate| {{citation<!--bibl info per http://hollis.harvard.edu/?itemid=|library/m/aleph|013970591-->\n| title='Titanic' disaster : hearings before a subcommittee of the Committee on Commerce United States Senate Sixty-second Congress Second Session pursuant to S. Res. 283, directing the Committee on Commerce to investigate the causes leading to the wreck of the White star liner 'Titanic'\n| author = United States. Congress. Senate. Committee on Commerce. | year =1912\n| publisher = Government Printing Office | work = 62nd Congress, no. 806\n| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QZ0qAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1107}} }}\n\n{{refn|name=panamerican| {{citation |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=fT09AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA778 |work = Bulletin of the Pan American Union |volume = 43 |number = 6 |page = 778 |date = Dec 1916 |title = The 'Alberta' leaving New York for the Amazon River |department = Pan American Notes }} }}\n\n{{refn|name=american_kennel_club| {{citation |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=EWQZAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA310 |page = 310 |title = Mrs. Eleanore Elkins Widener (31840) |work = Lineage Book \u2013 National Society of the Daughters of the American Revolution |year = 1911 |volume = 32 }} }}\n\n{{refn|name=titanica_eleanor_widener|{{cite web |title = Eleanor Widener |url = http://www.encyclopedia-titanica.org/titanic-survivor/eleanor-widener.html |website = Encyclopedia Titanica |accessdate = April 22, 2014 }}{{better source|date=April 2014}} }}\n\n{{refn|name=bentinck1976|{{cite book |title = Building a great library: the Coolidge years at Harvard |url = https://books.google.com/books/about/?id=zYYaAAAAMAAJ |year = 1976 |last = Bentinck-Smith |first = William |publisher = Harvard University Library |isbn = 978-0-674-08578-7 }} }}\n\n}}\n\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Books|Education|Literature|United States}}\n\n{{Commons category}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Widener, Eleanor Elkins}}\n[[Category:1860s births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Philadelphia Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:People from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:RMS Titanic survivors]]\n[[Category:Widener family]]\n", "name_user": "Hiabc", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove unnedded shy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eleanor_Elkins_Widener"}
{"title_page": "Z\u00e9 Elias", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Z\u00e9 Elias\n| image = Z\u00e9 Elias - SC Rheindorf Altach.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Z\u00e9 Elias in 2009\n| fullname = Jos\u00e9 Elias Moedim J\u00fanior\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|9|25|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Guarulhos]], Brazil\n| height = 1.78 m\n| position = [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]]<br>[[Central midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Sport Club Corinthians Paulista|Corinthians]]\n| years1 = 1993\u20131996 | clubs1 = [[Sport Club Corinthians Paulista|Corinthians]] | caps1 = 60 | goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 1996\u20131997 | clubs2 = [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] | caps2 = 23 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 1997\u20131999 | clubs3 = [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]] | caps3 = 33 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1999\u20132000 | clubs4 = [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] | caps4 = 19 | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2000\u20132003 | clubs5 = [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiakos]] | caps5 = 49 | goals5 = 2\n| years6 = 2003\u20132004 | clubs6 = [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]] | caps6 = 19 | goals6 = 1\n| years7 = 2004\u20132005 | clubs7 = [[Santos FC|Santos]] | caps7 = 25 | goals7 = 1\n| years8 = 2006 | clubs8 = [[FC Metalurh Donetsk|Metalurh Donetsk]] | caps8 = 0 | goals8 = 0\n| years9 = 2006 | clubs9 = [[Guarani Futebol Clube|Guarani]] | caps9 = 1 | goals9 = 0\n| years10 = 2006\u20132007 | clubs10 = [[AC Omonia|Omonia]] | caps10 = 12 | goals10 = 1\n| years11 = 2008 | clubs11 = [[Londrina Esporte Clube|Londrina]] | caps11 = | goals11 =\n| years12 = 2008\u20132009 | clubs12 = [[SC Rheindorf Altach|Rheindorf Altach]] | caps12 = 16 | goals12 = 0\n| totalcaps = 257 | totalgoals = 7\n| nationalyears1 = 1995\u20131999 | nationalteam1 = [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] | nationalcaps1 = 10 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{BRA}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Football]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Atlanta]]|[[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|Team Competition]]}}\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Elias Moedim J\u00fanior''' (born 25 September 1976), commonly known as '''Z\u00e9 Elias''', is a Brazilian former professional [[Association football|footballer]]. A [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive]] or [[Central midfielder|central midfielder]], he played for 12 teams in seven countries. He is a football analyst for [[ESPN Brasil]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Guarulhos]], Z\u00e9 Elias was one of the youngest players to ever appear for [[Sport Club Corinthians Paulista]]. He had already gained strong interest from [[PSV Eindhoven]] during his beginnings as a senior, which happened at the age of 17.\n\nAfter becoming an undisputed starter at Corinthians, and first appearing for the [[Brazil national football team|Brazil national team]] at 19, Z\u00e9 Elias went overseas, representing with moderate individual success [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen]], [[Inter Milan]], [[Bologna F.C. 1909]], [[Olympiacos F.C.]] and [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa CFC]]. He won three consecutive [[Superleague Greece]] championships with the fourth club, but appeared sparingly in the process (a maximum of 18 league appearances).\n\nAfter a return to Brazil with [[Santos FC]], Z\u00e9 Elias had short-lived stints with [[FC Metalurh Donetsk]], [[Guarani Futebol Clube]], [[AC Omonia]] and [[Londrina Esporte Clube]]. He retired as a player in March 2008, and assumed a [[Scout (sport)|scouting]] role in Brazil for Inter Milan; however, in June, he signed a contract with [[SC Rheindorf Altach]] for the [[2008\u201309 Austrian Football Bundesliga|2008\u201309 season]], before announcing his retirement again.\n\n==International career==\nZ\u00e9 Elias was [[Cap (sport)|capped]] ten times for [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]. He received his first call-up on 29 March 1995, in a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] with [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]] which ended 1\u20131.\n\nZ\u00e9 Elias represented [[Brazil national under-23 football team|the country]] at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]] where he [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|won bronze]], and later at the [[1996 CONCACAF Gold Cup]] in a runner-up finish, losing 0\u20132 in the final against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]].\n\n==Personal life==\nElias' younger brother, [[Rubinho (footballer)|Rubinho]], is also a professional footballer. A [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]], he played most of his career in Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2006/07/17/sorpresa-un-portiere-brasiliano-rubinho-fratello-di.html|title=Sorpresa: un portiere brasiliano \u00e8 Rubinho, fratello di Ze Elias|trans-title=Surprise: a Brazilian goalkeeper is Rubinho, Ze Elias's brother|newspaper=[[La Repubblica]]|language=Italian|date=17 July 2006|accessdate=11 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Corinthians'''\n*[[Campeonato Paulista]]: 1995\n*[[Copa do Brasil]]: [[1995 Copa do Brasil|1995]]\n\n'''Inter'''\n*[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]: [[1997\u201398 UEFA Cup|1997\u201398]]\n\n'''Olympiacos'''\n*[[Superleague Greece]]: [[2000\u201301 Alpha Ethniki|2000\u201301]], [[2001\u201302 Alpha Ethniki|2001\u201302]], [[2002\u201303 Alpha Ethniki|2002\u201303]]\n*[[Greek Football Cup]]: Runner-up [[2000\u201301 Greek Cup|2000\u201301]], [[2001\u201302 Greek Cup|2001\u201302]]\n\n'''Santos'''\n*[[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A]]: [[2004 Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|2004]]\n\n===International===\n'''Brazil'''\n*[[CONCACAF Gold Cup]]: Runner-up [[1996 CONCACAF Gold Cup|1996]]\n*[[Summer Olympic Games]]: Bronze medal [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Sambafoot|619_ze_elias}}\n*{{NFT|10151}}\n*{{FIFA player|193634}}\n\n{{navboxes colour\n| title=Brazil squad\n| bg= #FBEC5D\n| fg= #008000\n| 