{{sort|Fabulous Moolah|[[The Fabulous Moolah]]}}<br />({{small|Mary Ellison}})\n|{{sortname|Alundra|Blayze|Madusa}}\n| A four-time [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWF Women's Champion]] prior to her induction, her first reign is recognized as lasting a record 28 years<ref name=\"Moolah\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/fabulousmoolah/|title=The Fabulous Moolah|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{sort|Grand Wizard|[[Ernie Roth|The Grand Wizard]]}}<br />({{small|Irwin Roth}})\n|{{sortname|Sgt.|Slaughter}}\n|Posthumous inductee. <br/> Long-time heel manager in WWF<ref name=\"Wizard\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/thegrandwizard/|title=The Grand Wizard|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Pedro Morales as the WWWF (WWE) Champion.jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|Pedro|Morales}}\n|{{sortname|Savio|Vega}}\n|[[Savio Vega]] accepted the induction. One-time [[WWE Championship|WWWF World Heavyweight Champion]] whose reign lasted nearly three years, and the first [[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)|WWF Triple Crown Champion]]<ref name=\"Morales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/pedromorales/|title=Pedro Morales| publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref> He was also the first Latino to win the world title<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.bleacherreport.com/articles/445386-is-john-cena-the-greatest-champion-ever-ranking-all-46-wwe-world-champi#/articles/445386-is-john-cena-the-greatest-champion-ever-ranking-all-46-wwe-world-champi/page/38 |title=John Cena The Greatest Champion Ever? Ranking All 46 WWE World Champions \u221210. Pedro Morales |author=A. Version 2.0 |publisher=BleacherReport.com |date= September 1, 2010 |accessdate=December 23, 2011}}</ref>\n|-style=\"border-top:2px solid gray;\"\n|}\n\n===Class of 1996===\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name       = WWF Hall of Fame (1996)\n|caption    = \n|image      = \n|alt        =\n|tagline    = \n|theme      = \n|promotion  = [[WWE|WWF]]\n|brand      = \n|date       = {{dts|1996|11|16}}\n|venue      = [[New York Marriott Marquis|Marriott Marquis]]\n|city       = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|attendance = \n|lastevent  = \n|nextevent  = \n|event      = WWE Hall of Fame\n|lastevent2 = [[WWF Hall of Fame (1995)|1995]]\n|nextevent2 = [[WWE Hall of Fame (2004)|2004]]\n}}\n'''WWF Hall of Fame (1996)''' was the event which featured the introduction of the fourth class to the WWE Hall of Fame. The event was produced by the [[WWE|WWF]] on November 16, 1996 from the [[New York Marriott Marquis|Marriott Marquis]] in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. The event took place the same weekend as [[Survivor Series (1996)|Survivor Series]].\n\nIn March 2015 a condensed version of the ceremony was added to the [[WWE Network]].<ref name=networkadd /> Due to the original ceremony only being partially recorded and not originally intended to air, [[Gene Okerlund]] and [[Renee Young]] host the program with added commentary.\n\nDue to [[Vincent J. McMahon]]'s passing in 1984, he was posthumously inducted by the [[McMahon family]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Image\n! Ring name<br />(Birth Name)\n! Inducted by\n! class=\"unsortable\"| WWE recognized accolades\n|-\n|[[File:Baron Scicluna - Heavyweight Wrestling - 31 August 1970 (cropped).jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|\"Baron\" Mikel|Scicluna|Mikel Scicluna}}\n|{{sortname|Gorilla|Monsoon}}\n|One-time [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWWF World Tag Team Champion]] and one-time [[WWWF United States Tag Team Championship|WWWF United States Tag Team Champion]]<ref name=\"Scicluna\">{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/superstars/baronmikelscicluna/|title=\"Baron\" Mikel Scicluna|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Lou Albano and a fan crop.jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|\"Captain\" Lou|Albano|Lou Albano}}\n|{{sortname|Joe|Franklin}}\n| One-time [[WWWF United States Tag Team Championship|WWWF United States Tag Team Champion]]. As a manager, he led 13 different tag teams to a record 17 tag team titles,<ref>The Wrestler magazine, various X-ray panels</ref> and four singles wrestlers to various championships. His association with [[Cyndi Lauper]] was pivotal in turning professional wrestling into a mainstream phenomenon<ref name=\"Albano\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/captainloualbano/|title=\"Captain\" Lou Albano|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate= April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Jimmy Superfly Snuka Paparazzo Photography.jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|Jimmy \"Superfly\"|Snuka|Jimmy Snuka}}\n|{{sortname|Don|Muraco}}\n|One-time [[WWE United States Championship|NWA United States Heavyweight Champion]], two-time [[WCW World Tag Team Championship|NWA World Tag Team Champion]], two-time [[ECW Championship|ECW Heavyweight Champion]]<ref name=\"Snuka\">{{cite web| url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/jimmysnuka/|title=Jimmy \"Superfly\" Snuka|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Johnny Rodz.jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|Johnny|Rodz}}<br />({{small|John Rodriguez}})\n|{{sortname|Arnold|Skaaland}}\n|Wrestled in [[World Wrestling Entertainment|WWF]] for nearly two decades<ref name=\"Rodz\">{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/superstars/johnnyrodz/|title=Johnny Rodz|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate= April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Killer Kowalski - Wrestling - International Amphitheatre - Chicago Wrestling Mars 6, programme 1953 - Cover (cropped).jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|Killer|Kowalski}}<br />({{small|Edward Spulnik}})\n|[[Triple H]]\n|One-time [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWWF World Tag Team Champion]], held seventeen NWA regional championships<ref name=\"Kowalski\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/killerkowalski/|title=Ki