Arena]]\n|Gene Okerlund and Todd Grisham\n|{{sort|24|[[WrestleMania XXIV]]}}\n|-\n|{{dts|2009|4|4}}\n|[[Houston|Houston, Texas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/schedules/events/eventdetail/?id=8873388|title=WWE Hall of Fame 2009 Ticket Info|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=February 15, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224205832/http://www.wwe.com/schedules/events/eventdetail/?id=8873388|archivedate=February 24, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|[[Toyota Center]]\n|Jerry Lawler and Todd Grisham\n|{{sort|25|[[WrestleMania XXV]]}}\n|-\n|{{dts|2010|3|27}}\n|[[Phoenix, Arizona]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/schedules/events/rw/eventdetail/13171052|title=WWE Hall of Fame 2010 Ticket Info|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=January 7, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100122104413/http://www.wwe.com/schedules/events/rw/eventdetail/13171052|archivedate=January 22, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|[[Dodge Theater]]\n|rowspan=9|Jerry Lawler\n|{{sort|26|[[WrestleMania XXVI]]}}\n|-\n|{{dts|2011|4|2}}\n|[[Atlanta, Georgia]]<ref name=\"Bid\">{{cite web|url=http://atlanta.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2009/09/28/story6.html|first=Lisa R.|last=Schoolcraft| title=Atlanta is bidding for WrestleMania|work=[[American City Business Journals|Atlanta Business Chronicle]]|date=September 25, 2009| accessdate=February 1, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=August 2010|title=[[WWE Magazine]]|page=69}}</ref>\n|[[State Farm Arena (Atlanta)|Phillips Arena]]\n|{{sort|27|[[WrestleMania XXVII]]}}\n|-\n|{{dts|2012|3|31}}\n|[[Miami, Florida]]<ref name=\"WWE-Press\">{{cite web|url=http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2011/wwe-corporate-miami-to-host-wrestlemania-xxviii|title=Miami to host WrestleMania XXVII|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|date=March 27, 2011|accessdate=February 9, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402095631/http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2011/wwe-corporate-miami-to-host-wrestlemania-xxviii|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|[[American Airlines Arena]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2011/02/11/v-fullstory/2061324/diaz-mcmahon-sophia-bring-wrestlemania.html|title=Diaz, McMahon, Sophia bring WrestleMania 28 to Miami|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|date=February 11, 2011|accessdate=February 12, 2011}}</ref>\n|{{sort|28|[[WrestleMania XXVIII]]}}\n|-\n|{{dts|2013|4|6}}\n|[[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|[[Madison Square Garden]]\n|{{sort|29|[[WrestleMania 29]]}}\n|-\n|{{dts|2014|4|5}}\n|[[New Orleans, Louisiana]]\n|[[Smoothie King Center]]\n|{{sort|30|[[WrestleMania XXX]]}}\n|-\n|{{dts|2015|3|28}}\n|[[San Jose, California]]\n|[[SAP Center]]<ref name=\"WWE-Corporate\">{{cite web|url=http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2013/wwe-corporate-silicon-valley-to-host-wrestlemania|title=Silicon Valley to host WrestleMania|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|date=December 10, 2013|accessdate=March 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402105441/http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2013/wwe-corporate-silicon-valley-to-host-wrestlemania|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|{{sort|31|[[WrestleMania 31]]}}\n|-\n|{{dts|2016|4|2}}\n|[[Dallas, Texas]]\n|[[American Airlines Center]]\n|{{sort|32|[[WrestleMania 32]]}}\n|-\n|{{dts|2017|3|31}}\n|[[Orlando, Florida]]\n|[[Amway Center]]\n|{{sort|33|[[WrestleMania 33]]}}\n|-\n|{{dts|2018|4|6}}\n|[[New Orleans, Louisiana]]\n|[[Smoothie King Center]]\n|{{sort|34|[[WrestleMania 34]]}}\n|-\n|{{dts|2019|4|6}}\n|[[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|[[Barclays Center]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2018/03/15/wrestlemania-is-coming-back-to-metlife-stadium/|title=WrestleMania is coming back to MetLife Stadium|date=2018-03-16|work=New York Post|access-date=2018-03-30|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.charitybuzz.com/catalog_items/suite-for-10-at-wrestlemania-35-plus-tickets-to-wwe-1496524|title=Suite for 10 at WrestleMania 35 Plus Tickets to WWE Hall of Fame Ceremony & WrestleMania Axxess Sessions April 5\u20137, 2019|publisher=Charitybuzz|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>\n|[[Corey Graves]] and [[Renee Young]]\n|{{sort|34|[[WrestleMania 35]]}}\n|}\n\n==Reception==\nIn 2012, ''[[The Post and Courier]]'' columnist Mike Mooneyham noted that the Hall has garnered criticism due to the inductions of questionable performers, and the omissions of major names within the industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20120115/PC1203/301159980|title=Four Horsemen back in the saddle|last=Mooneyham|first=Mike|date=January 15, 2012|website=[[The Post and Courier]]|publisher=[[Evening Post Industries]]|access-date=January 4, 2015|quote=The WWE Hall has been criticized in the past for a number of questionable selections as well as notable omissions.}}</ref> Bob Backlund declined induction multiple times,<ref name=\"eck\">[http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/sports/wrestling/blog/2008/02/analyzing_the_wwe_hall_of_fame.html Kevin Eck, Baltimore Sun]</ref> and The Ultimate Warrior wrote that he refused the honor in 2010;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ultimatewarrior.com/blog/?p=149|title=Wayback Machine|date=2010-03-29|access-date=2018-02-15|df=mdy-all}}</ref> they were eventually inducted in 2013 and 2014, respectively. Randy Savage was recognized as being noticeably absent;<ref>{{cite news|title=WWE Hall of Fame again spurns Macho Man|url=http://tbo.com/news/wwe-hall-of-fame-against-spurns-macho-man-20140331/|last=Guzzel|first=Paul|work=The Tampa Tribune|date=March 31, 2014|accessdate=August 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170722111416/http://www.tbo.com/news/wwe-hall-of-fame-against-spurns-macho-man-20140331/|archive-date=July 22, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Chris Jericho]] said that the Hall achieved a level of legitimacy by inducting him in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tufayel|first=Ahmed|title= Chris Jericho: 'WWE Hall of Fame NEEDS to induct Macho Man for credibility' |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/chris-jericho-wwe-hall-fame-4986566|date=April 8, 2011|accessdate=September 22, 2016|work=[[The Daily Mirror]]}}</ref> ''Slam Wrestling'' questioned how Koko B. Ware, who primarily wrestled in the [[Undercard (professional wrestling)|undercard]], was inducted but former WWWF World Heavyweight Champion [[Ivan Koloff]] never was before his 2017 death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/MatMatters/2017/02/19/22705280.html|title= Mat Matters: WWE Hall of Fame's unforgiveable shunning of Ivan Koloff |last=Smith|first=Caleb|work=SLAM! Wrestling|publisher=[[Canoe.ca|Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=March 4, 2017}}</ref> Koko B. Ware, who worked as an undercard wrestler in WWF, is often billed as a controversial inductee since he was selected before most relevant wrestlers like Randy Savage or Bruno Sammartino.<ref>https://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/The_Specialists_34/article_30610.shtml#.XfN5d2RKiUk</ref><ref>https://www.wrestleview.com/uncategorized/11233-the-shoot-6/</ref><ref>https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/46240-jake-roberts-on-wwe-return-ultimate-warrior-hof-induction/</ref><ref>https://411mania.com/wrestling/the-411-on-wrestling-podcast-breaking-down-the-latest-wwe-releases-hall-of-fame-inductees-previewing-roh-final-battle-nwa-into-the-fire-2019/</ref><ref>https://www.pwinsider.com/article/44732/no-bret-hart-in-canada-hogans-role-in-tna-the-kongbubba-fight-wwe-hall-of-fame-and-more.html?p=1</ref> In 2020, 411Mania writers Steve Cook and Kevin Pantoja discussed Ware's induction. While Cook defended his Hall of Fame status since he was very over and some of his losses were historic, Pantoja described him as \"the floor for inductees\".<ref>https://411mania.com/wrestling/411-wrestling-fact-or-fiction-will-cody-vs-mjf-steal-the-show-at-aew-revolution/</ref>\n\nBruno Sammartino, the longest reigning WWWF World Heavyweight Champion, was once critical of the Hall of Fame. Sammartino disapproved of celebrity inductees such as Pete Rose and William Perry, and said of the ceremony: \"What's the point to a Hall of Fame? Is it a building I can actually go to? No. Give me a break\".<ref name=\"Slam2\">{{cite web|last=MacKinder|first=Matt|title=Sammartino: McMahon is 'a sick-minded idiot|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2007/04/16/4035027.html|date=April 16, 2007|accessdate=May 6, 2007|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|work=SLAM! Sports&nbsp;\u2014 Wrestling}}</ref> Sammartino declined previous induction offers, before accepting in 2013. Paul Levesque (Triple H) said that it was important for Sammartino to be inducted from a \"legitimacy standpoint\" and [[ESPN]] said that his induction is an opportunity to legitimize the Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"Bruno2013\">{{cite news|title=WWE to induct Bruno Sammartino into HOF|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/playbook/fandom/post/_/id/17789/wwe-to-induct-bruno-sammartino-into-hof|publisher=ESPN|date=February 4, 2013}}</ref> After being announced as an inductee, Sammartino said he considered the Hall to be legitimate.<ref>{{cite news|title= WWE News: Update on physical Hall of Fame building |url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_68530.shtml|last=Caldwell|first=James|work=PWTorch|date=February 9, 2013|accessdate=February 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSuperstar Billy Graham publicly slammed the hall and demanded that WWE remove him from it, due to the 2011 induction of Abdullah the Butcher. Graham wrote: \"It is a shameless organization to induct a bloodthirsty animal such as Abdullah the Butcher into their worthless and embarrassing Hall of Fame and I want the name of Superstar Billy Graham to be no part of it\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Baines|first=Tim|title=Superstar Graham would spit on Jericho's grave, wants out of WWE HOF|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2011/04/08/17929556.html|date=April 8, 2011|accessdate=January 19, 2016|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|work=SLAM! Sports&nbsp;\u2014 Wrestling}}</ref> [[Sabu (wrestler)|Sabu]] also criticized the Hall of Fame, saying \"I'd only do it because I need the money... I don't consider it a real Hall of Fame.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/extra-mustard/2017/01/23/wwe-sabu-vince-mcmahon-hip-replacement-interview|title=At 52 and coming off a hip replacement, Sabu just wants to keep wrestling|last=Barrasso|first=Justin|date=January 23, 2017|website=[[Sports Illustrated]]|access-date=February 6, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, Bret Hart, who headlined the 2006 ceremony, criticized the omissions of several wrestlers, primarily [[Dynamite Kid]] and his brother [[Owen Hart|Owen]], as well as the inductions of the likes of The Rock 'n' Roll Express and The Fabulous Freebirds, who experienced little success in WWE. Hart said he would not go to another ceremony until WWE inducts \"proper, deserving candidates\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=Brian|title=Bret Hart on why Owen Hart should be in the WWE Hall of Fame and what's keeping him out|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/bret-hart-on-why-owen-hart-should-be-in-the-wwe-hall-of-fame-and-whats-keeping-him-out/|date=July 5, 2018|accessdate=August 25, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]}}</ref> During an interview in 2019, Ric Flair also said there is several wrestlers in the Hall of Fame that didn't deserve it, but he didn't name names.<ref>https://www.wrestlinginc.com/news/2019/12/ric-flair-talks-batista-going-into-the-wwe-hall-of-fame-663419/</ref>\n\nOthers have offered praise for the Hall of Fame. [[World Wrestling Council]] promoter and 26-time [[WWC Universal Heavyweight Championship|WWC Universal Heavyweight Champion]] [[Carlos Col\u00f3n Sr.]] said that his 2014 induction was a \"realization of a dream\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Jim\u00e9nez |first=Lester|title=Exaltar\u00e1n a Carlos Col\u00f3n al Sal\u00f3n de la Fama de la WWE|url=https://www.primerahora.com/deportes/otros/nota/exaltaranacarloscolonalsalondelafamadelawwe-995096/|date=March 11, 2014|accessdate=September 3, 2019|work=[[Primera Hora (Puerto Rico)|Primera Hora]]|language=Spanish}}</ref> 2015 Hall of Fame headliner Kevin Nash stated that two things in the professional wrestling business are real: \"When you win your first championship and when you get inducted into the Hall of Fame.\" Nash claimed this is a sentiment to which colleague Ric Flair also subscribes.<ref>{{cite news|title= 2015 WWE Hall of Fame live coverage: Randy Savage, Kevin Nash, Larry Zbyszko, Madusa/Alundra Blayze, The Bushwhackers, Tatsumi Fujinami, Connor Michalek, and Arnold Schwarzenegger|url=http://prowrestling.net/article.php?2015-WWE-Hall-of-Fame-live-coverage-Randy-Savage-Kevin-Nash-Larry-Zbyszko-Madusa-Alundra-Blayze-The-Bushwhackers-Tatsumi-Fujinami-Connor-Michalek-and-Arnold-Schwarzenegger-41550|work=prowrestling.net|date=March 28, 2015|accessdate=January 20, 2016}}</ref> During his 2013 induction, future U.S. president Donald Trump said that the honor meant more than \"having the highest ratings in TV, being a best-selling author or getting a spot on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Dawsey|first=Josh|title= Trump\u2019s obsession with WrestleMania and fake drama |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/01/trump-wrestlemania-fake-233615|date=January 16, 2017|accessdate=February 22, 2017|publisher=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Dave Scherer]] of ''[[PWInsider]]'' has questioned how WWE can sustain the 2004\u2013present Hall of Fame model, due to legends being rapidly inducted. He wrote: \"There are only so many people that they can have headline a class. They really need to make more new stars to ensure that they can keep filling arenas for the ceremony\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/98773/the-rock-at-wrestlemania-running-out-of-headliners-for-the-hall-of-fame-touring-wwe-hq-and-more.html|title=The Rock at WrestleMania, running out of headliners for the Hall of Fame, touring WWE HQ and more|last=Scherer|first=Dave|date=January 4, 2016|website=PWInsider|access-date=March 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[WrestleMania Axxess#Hall of Fame statue|WWE Hall of Fame statue]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Featured list}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|https://www.wwe.com/shows/wwe-hall-of-fame}}\n\n{{WWE}}\n{{WWE Hall of Fame}}\n{{Professional wrestling halls of fame}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wwe Hall Of Fame}}\n[[Category:Awards established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Halls of fame in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Hall of fame inductees]]\n[[Category:WrestleMania|Hall of Fame]]\n[[Category:WWE Hall of Fame| ]]\n[[Category:WWE lists|Hall of Fame]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Professional wrestling hall of fame and television show}}\n<noinclude>{{pp-protected|small=yes}}</noinclude>\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name = WWE Hall of Fame\n|image = WWE Hall of Fame Logo, 2019 version.png\n|image_size = 250px\n|caption = WWE Hall of Fame logo since 2019\n|formation = {{start date and age|1993|03|22}}\n|members = '''204 total inductees'''<br><small>113 Individual inductees<br>37 Legacy inductees<br>15 Group inductees<br>10 Celebrity inductees<br>5 Warrior Award inductees</small>\n|website = {{official website|https://www.wwe.com/shows/wwe-hall-of-fame|WWE Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n\nThe '''WWE Hall of Fame''' is a [[List of halls and walks of fame|hall of fame]] which honors [[professional wrestlers]] and professional wrestling personalities maintained by [[WWE]]. Originally known as the \"WWF Hall of Fame\", it was created in 1993, when [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]] was posthumously inducted with a video package. The 1994 and 1995 ceremonies were held in conjunction with the annual [[King of the Ring]] pay-per-view events and the 1996 ceremony was held with the [[Survivor Series]] event. After an eight year hiatus, WWE relaunched the Hall of Fame in 2004 and has held the ceremonies in conjunction with [[WrestleMania]] ever since. Since 2005, portions of the induction ceremonies have aired on television and since 2014 the entire ceremonies have aired on the [[WWE Network]].\n\nAs of 2019, there have been 204 inductees, with 113 wrestlers inducted individually,  37 Legacy Inductees, 15 group inductions (consisting of 43 wrestlers within those groups), 10 celebrities and five Warrior Award recipients, whilst 57 members have been inducted posthumously. Four wrestlers have been inducted twice (individually and as part of a tag team/group): [[Ric Flair]], [[Shawn Michaels]], [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]], and [[Bret Hart]], with four more ([[Hulk Hogan]], [[Scott Hall]], [[Kevin Nash]], and [[Sean Waltman]]) to receive a second induction in 2020.<ref name=\"HoF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/halloffame/|title=WWE Hall of Fame|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe WWF Hall of Fame was created in 1993. It was first announced on the March 22, 1993 episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Monday Night Raw]]'' where [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]], who had died nearly two months prior, was announced as the sole inductee.<ref>[http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/93.htm 1993 WWF results, from TheHistoryOfWWE.com]</ref><ref name=\"WWFRawMar22\">{{cite episode|title=WWF Monday Night Raw (March 22, 1993)|series=WWF Monday Night Raw|serieslink=WWE Raw|credits=World Wrestling Federation employees|network= USA Network|airdate=1993-03-22|season=1}}</ref><ref name=\"Andre\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/andrethegiant/|title=Andre the Giant|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]| accessdate=February 15, 2009}}</ref> In the proceeding two years, induction ceremonies were held in conjunction with the annual [[King of the Ring]] pay-per-view events. The 1996 ceremony was held with the [[Survivor Series]] event, for the first time in front of a paying audience as well as the wrestlers, after which, the Hall of Fame went on hiatus.\n\nWWE (WWF changed its name to WWE in 2002) relaunched the Hall of Fame in 2004 to coincide with [[WrestleMania XX]].<ref name=\"2004h\">{{cite web|url=http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2004/wwe-corporate-pete-rose-to-be-inducted-into-wwe-hall-of-fame|title=Pete Rose to Be Inducted Into Hall Of Fame.World Wrestling Entertainment Hall Of Fame|date=March 2, 2004|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]] Corporate|accessdate=February 15, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402151205/http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2004/wwe-corporate-pete-rose-to-be-inducted-into-wwe-hall-of-fame|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> This ceremony, like its predecessors, was not broadcast on television. However, it was released on [[DVD]] on June 1, 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fye.com/WWE--Hall-of-Fame-2004-Induction-Ceremony--2-Discs--WWE_stcVVproductId2613213VVcatId515097VVviewprod.htm|title=WWE Hall of Fame 2004 Induction Ceremony|publisher=[[Trans World Entertainment|For Your Entertainment]]|accessdate=February 15, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221231240/http://www.fye.com/WWE--Hall-of-Fame-2004-Induction-Ceremony--2-Discs--WWE_stcVVproductId2613213VVcatId515097VVviewprod.htm|archivedate=February 21, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Beginning with the 2005 ceremony, an edited version of the Hall of Fame was broadcast on [[Spike TV]] (2005)<ref name=\"2005h\">{{cite web|url=http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2005/wwe-corporate-world-wrestling-entertainment-invades-los-angeles-starting-tuesday-march-29-with-series-of-public-events-as-part-of-wrestlemania-21-week|title=World Wrestling Entertainment Invades Los Angeles Starting Tuesday, March 29, With Series of Public Events As Part of WrestleMania 21 Week|date=March 23, 2005|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]] Corporate|accessdate=February 15, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402154314/http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2005/wwe-corporate-world-wrestling-entertainment-invades-los-angeles-starting-tuesday-march-29-with-series-of-public-events-as-part-of-wrestlemania-21-week|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and on the [[USA Network]] (2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2006/wwe-corporate-world-wrestling-entertainment-blows-big-time-into-chicago-starting-tuesday-march-28-with-a-series-of-public-events-as-part-of-wrestlemania-22-week|title=World Wrestling Entertainment Blows \"Big Time\" Into Chicago Starting Tuesday, March 28, With A Series of Public Events As Part of WrestleMania 22 Week|date=March 22, 2006|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]] Corporate|accessdate=February 15, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402101422/http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2006/wwe-corporate-world-wrestling-entertainment-blows-big-time-into-chicago-starting-tuesday-march-28-with-a-series-of-public-events-as-part-of-wrestlemania-22-week|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\u2013present<ref name=\"Wrestleview1\">{{cite web|url= http://www.wrestleview.com/news2008/1206782374.shtml|title=2008 WWE Hall of Fame airs live on WWE.com & USA tonight and more|last= Martin|first=Adam|date=March 29, 2008|publisher=WrestleView.com|accessdate=February 15, 2009}}</ref>); these were aired on [[broadcast delay|tape delay]]. Since 2005, the entire Hall of Fame ceremony has been packaged as part of the annual WrestleMania DVD release,<ref>[[WrestleMania 21]], [[WrestleMania 22|22]], [[WrestleMania 23|23]], and [[WrestleMania XXIV|XXIV]] DVD's</ref> and from 2014, has been broadcast live on the [[WWE Network]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/videos/triple-h-reveals-the-2014-wwe-hall-of-fame-induction-ceremony-with-be-broadcast-26181593|title=Triple H reveals the 2014 WWE Hall of Fame induction ceremony will be broadcast on WWE Network|date=February 12, 2014|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=April 8, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140308014805/http://www.wwe.com/videos/triple-h-reveals-the-2014-wwe-hall-of-fame-induction-ceremony-with-be-broadcast-26181593|archivedate=March 8, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2015, historical WWE Hall of Fame ceremonies became available on the WWE Network.\n\nAlthough a building has never been built to represent the Hall of Fame, WWE has looked into constructing a facility. In 2008, [[Shane McMahon]], then-Executive Vice President of Global Media of WWE, stated that WWE had been storing wrestling memorabilia in a warehouse for years, with all items categorized and dated in case a facility is created.<ref name=\"Facility\">{{cite web|last=Scherer|first=Dave|title=SmackDown Rating, WWE Looking For A Location to Create A Hall of Fame, The Bash, and more|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=30289&p=1|date= April 8, 2008| accessdate=March 20, 2015|publisher=PWInsider}}</ref>\n\n==Specialty inductees==\n\n===Celebrity wing===\nThe \"celebrity wing\" of the Hall of Fame is dedicated to celebrities that have made memorable appearances on WWE programming, and/or have had longtime associations with WWE.\n\n===Warrior Award===\n[[File:Dana Warrior Award.jpg|right|thumb|upright|[[Dana Warrior]] presents the inaugural Warrior Award at the 2015 Hall of Fame ceremony]]\nIn 2015, WWE introduced the Warrior Award for those who have \"exhibited unwavering strength and perseverance, and who lives life with the courage and compassion that embodies the indomitable spirit of the Ultimate Warrior.\"<ref name=\"Connor\">{{Cite web|title=WWE fan Connor Michalek to receive first-ever Warrior Award at 2015 WWE Hall of Fame Induction Ceremony|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/wwe-hall-of-fame/connor-michalek-warrior-award-2015-27168837|publisher=WWE|date=March 9, 2015|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhile WWE promotes Warrior Award recipients as Hall of Fame inductees,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/03/wwe-connor-the-crusher-michalik-hall-of-fame|title=WWE Superfan Connor \"The Crusher\" Michalek to be inducted into Hall of Fame|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=2015-03-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=WWE|author=WWE|number=575097848041181184|date=10 March 2015|title=Donate today to @ConnorsCure, on behalf of #ConnorTheCrusher: #RAW #WWEHOF}}</ref> they are not included in the Hall of Fame section at WWE.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/videos/playlists/wwe-hall-of-fame-2015-inductions|title=WWE HOF Class of 2015|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=2015-03-28}}</ref> and an image gallery which shows \"every WWE Hall of Famer ever\" does not contain any recipient.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/wwe-hall-of-fame/every-wwe-hall-of-famer-ever-photos|title=Every WWE Hall of Famer ever: photos|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=2016-03-31}}</ref>\n\nThe award was created following [[The Ultimate Warrior]]'s death. During his April 2014 Hall of Fame speech shortly before his death, he proposed that there be a special category called the \"Jimmy Miranda Award\" for WWE's behind-the-scenes employees.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Jason|title=2014 WWE Hall of Fame live coverage: Ultimate Warrior, Jake Roberts, Lita, Razor Ramon, Paul Bearer, and Carlos Colon|url=http://prowrestling.net/article.php?36479|website=prowrestling.net|accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Warrior had cardiovascular disease|url=http://espn.go.com/espn/story/_/id/10782037/ultimate-warrior-died-cardiovascular-disease|agency=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref> Miranda, who died in 2002, was part of the WWE merchandise department for more than 20 years<ref>{{cite web|last1=Martin|first1=Adam|title=WWE Raw Results (July 15, 2002)|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/82.shtml|website=wrestleview.com|accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref> Former WWE ring announcer [[Justin Roberts]] expressed disappointment at how WWE used portions of Warrior's Hall of Fame speech to promote the award, but left out Warrior's intentions of honoring WWE's off-screen employees<ref name=RobertsTorch>{{cite web|title=[Updated with WWE statement] former WWE ring announcer Justin Roberts blogs on Connor induction to WWE Hall of Fame, WWE's usage of Conner|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=92820|website=pwinsider.com|accessdate=4 April 2015|last1=Johnson|first=Mike}}</ref><ref name=RobertsInsider>{{cite web|title=Former ring announcer Justin Roberts questions sincerity of WWE's relationship with Connor the Crusher|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_84260.shtml|website=PWTorch.com|accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref> WWE responded, \"It is offensive to suggest that WWE and its executives had anything but altruistic intentions in honoring [[Connor Michalek|Connor]] and his legacy with The Warrior Award\", adding that \"moving forward the award will be given annually to acknowledge other unsung heroes among WWE's employees and fans\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=Mike|title=[Updated With WWE Statement] Former WWE ring announcer Justin Roberts blogs on Connor Induction to WWE Hall Of Fame, WWE's usage of Conner|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=92820|website=pwinsider.com|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref> 2019's recipient, Sue Aitchison, is the only WWE employee to receive the award thus far.<ref>{{cite web|title=WWE Is Giving This Year\u2019s Warrior Award To Longtime Employee Sue Aitchison|url=http://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/wwe-warrior-award-sue-aitchison/#.XJSjSMlKizc|website=Pro Wrestling Sheet|last=Quarrington|first=Norm|date=March 18, 2019|accessdate=March 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nTraditionally, [[Dana Warrior]] (widow of The Ultimate Warrior) presents the award.\n\n===Legacy inductees===\nIn 2016, WWE introduced a new category for the Hall of Fame called the \"Legacy\" wing. Inductees in this category are from several eras of wrestling history, going back to the early 20th century.<ref name=Legacy>{{cite web|title= Congratulations to the 2016 WWE Hall of Fame Legacy inductees |url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwe-hall-fame/wwe-hall-fame-2016/article/legacy-inductees|publisher=WWE|date=April 2, 2016|accessdate=April 2, 2016}}</ref> All but two inductees, [[Hisashi Shinma]] and [[MSG Network]] creator Joseph Cohen, have been inducted posthumously. Legacy inductees are recognized with a video package at the ceremonies.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|title= 4/2 WWE Hall of Fame Report \u2013 Complete Live Coverage of Sting, Freebirds, more inducted, plus Red Carpet Report|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/02/2016hofreport/|work=PWTorch.com|date=April 2, 2016|accessdate=April 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"2019a\">{{cite web|last1=Nason|first1=Josh|title=WWE Hall of Fame live coverage: DX headlines the 2019 class|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-hall-fame-live-coverage-dx-headlines-2019-class-281046|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|date=April 6, 2019|accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Legacy wing also has some criticism around it, specifically regarding the abbreviated way of the inductions. Professional wrestling journalist [[Dave Meltzer]] said \"this is the category they (WWE) use to honor people who, for whatever reason, they don't feel are marketable names to the modern audience to put in their actual Hall of Fame\".<ref>{{cite magazine| last =Meltzer| first =Dave| author-link =Dave Meltzer| title =April 22, 2019 Observer Newsletter| magazine =[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]| date =April 22, 2019}}</ref> In contrast, long time pro wrestling promoter and manager [[Jim Cornette]] critiziced the fact that recognizable names like [[Jim Londos]] or [[El Santo]] were part of a video package.<ref>{{cite episode| title =Episode 48| url =http://www.mlwradio.com/download-jim-cornette-s-drive-thru.html| series =Jim Cornette's Drive-Thru| air-date =April 9, 2018| access-date =April 19, 2019| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20190419180754/http://www.mlwradio.com/download-jim-cornette-s-drive-thru.html| archivedate =April 19, 2019| url-status =dead}}</ref> Bruiser Brody's widow stated that she did not know her husband was going to be inducted into the 2019 class until the day of the event and that she was not invited to the ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Satin|first1=Ryan|authorlink=Ryan Satin|title=Bruiser Brody\u2019s Widow Wasn\u2019t Invited to His WWE Hall of Fame Induction (Video) |url=http://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/bruiser-brody-widow-wwe-hall-fame/|work=Pro Wrestling Sheet|date=May 3, 2019|accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Classes==\n===Class of 1993===\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name       = WWF Hall of Fame (1993)\n|caption    = \n|image      = \n|alt        =\n|tagline    = \n|theme      = \n|promotion  = [[WWE|WWF]]\n|brand      = \n|date       = \n|venue      = \n|city       = \n|attendance = \n|lastevent  = \n|nextevent  = \n|event      = WWE Hall of Fame\n|lastevent2 = ''First''\n|nextevent2 = [[WWF Hall of Fame (1994)|1994]]\n}}\n'''WWF Hall of Fame (1993)''' was the inaugural class of the WWE Hall of Fame. During the March 22, 1993 episode of ''Monday Night Raw'' a video package announcing Andr\u00e9 the Giant's induction was shown.<ref name=\"Andre\"/> No ceremony took place, and Andr\u00e9 was inducted posthumously. In March 2015 a condensed version of the [[WWF Hall of Fame (1994)|1994 ceremony]] was added to the [[WWE Network]].<ref name=networkadd /> Due to no original ceremony, the 1993 introduction of Andr\u00e9 was discussed by [[Gene Okerlund]] and [[Renee Young]] as part of the 1994 commentary.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Image\n! Ring name<br />(Birth Name)\n! Inducted by\n! class=\"unsortable\"| WWE recognized accolades\n|-\n|[[File:Andr\u00e9 the Giant in the late '80s.jpg|75px]]\n|{{sort|Andre the Giant|'''[[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]]'''}}<br />({{small|Andr\u00e9 Roussimoff}})\n|None\n|One-time [[WWE Championship|WWF World Heavyweight Champion]], one-time [[WWF Tag Team Championship|WWF World Tag Team Champion]].<ref name=\"Andre\"/>\n|-style=\"border-top:2px solid gray;\"\n|}\n\n===Class of 1994===\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name       = WWF Hall of Fame (1994)\n|caption    = \n|image      = \n|alt        =\n|tagline    = \n|theme      = \n|promotion  = [[WWE|WWF]]\n|brand      = \n|date       = {{dts|1994|6|9}}\n|venue      = [[Radisson Hotel Baltimore Downtown-Inner Harbor|Omni Inner Harbor International Hotel]]\n|city       = [[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n|attendance = \n|lastevent  = \n|nextevent  = \n|event      = WWE Hall of Fame\n|lastevent2 = [[WWF Hall of Fame (1993)|1993]]\n|nextevent2 = [[WWF Hall of Fame (1995)|1995]]\n}}\n'''WWF Hall of Fame (1994)''' was the event which featured introduction of the second class to the WWE Hall of Fame. The event was produced by the [[WWE|WWF]] on June 6, 1994 from the [[Radisson Hotel Baltimore Downtown-Inner Harbor|Omni Inner Harbor International Hotel]] in [[Baltimore, Maryland]]. The event took place the same weekend as [[King of the Ring (1994)|King of the Ring]].\n\nIn March 2015 a condensed version of the ceremony was added to the [[WWE Network]].<ref name=networkadd>{{cite web|url=http://wrestlingnews.co/wwe-news/the-wwe-hall-of-fame-1994-1995-and-1996-ceremonies-on-the-wwe-network/|title=The WWE Hall of Fame 1994, 1995, and 1996 ceremonies are up on the WWE Network \u2013 Wrestling News|date=20 March 2015|publisher=|accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref> Due to the original ceremony only being partially recorded and not originally intended to air, [[Gene Okerlund]] and [[Renee Young]] host the program with added commentary.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Image\n! Ring name<br />(Birth Name)\n! Inducted by\n! class=\"unsortable\"| WWE recognized accolades\n|-\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{sortname|Arnold|Skaaland}}\n|{{sortname|Bob|Backlund}}\n|One-time [[WWWF United States Tag Team Championship|WWWF United States Tag Team Champion]] and long-time manager of [[Bruno Sammartino]] and [[Bob Backlund]] in WWF<ref name=\"Skaaland\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/arnoldskaaland/|title=Arnold Skaaland| publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Bobo Brazil - 1972 BODY PRESS WRESTLING MAGAZINE (cropped).jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|Bobo|Brazil}}<br />({{small|Houston Harris}})\n|{{sortname|Ernie|Ladd}}\n|Seven-time [[WWWF United States Heavyweight Championship|WWWF United States Heavyweight Champion]], one-time [[WWE United States Championship|NWA United States Heavyweight Champion]]<ref name=\"Brazil\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/bobobrazil/|title=Bobo Brazil|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Buddy Rogers Classic Wrestling.jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|Buddy|Rogers|Buddy Rogers (wrestler)}}<br />({{small|Herman Rohde Jr.}})\n|{{sortname|Bret|Hart}}\n|Posthumous inductee: One-time [[NWA World Heavyweight Championship|NWA World Heavyweight Champion]] and first [[WWE Championship|WWWF World Heavyweight Champion]]<ref name=\"Rogers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/buddyrogers/|title=\"Nature Boy\" Buddy Rogers|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Chief Jay Strongbow - Heavyweight Wrestling - 31 August 1970.jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|Chief Jay|Strongbow}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/staff/mike_mooneyham/pro-wrestling-great-chief-jay-strongbow-dead-at/article_b779dc63-67c1-58ec-9766-11a1fa7adb23.html|title=Pro wrestling great Chief Jay Strongbow dead at 83|publisher=|accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref><br />({{small|Luke Scarpa}})\n|[[Tatanka (wrestler)|Tatanka]]\n|Four-time [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWWF/WWF World Tag Team Champion]]<ref name=\"Strongbow\">{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/superstars/cheifjaystrongbow/|title=Chief Jay Strongbow|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Freddie Blassie.jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|\"Classy\" Freddie|Blassie|Freddie Blassie}}\n|[[Regis Philbin]]\n|Held over 30 NWA regional championships. Long-time manager in WWF<ref name=\"Blassie\">{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/superstars/freddieblassie/|title=\"Classy\" Freddie Blassie|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Gorilla Monsoon - Wrestling Program WWWF n.74 1977 (cropped).jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|Gorilla|Monsoon}}<br />({{small|Robert Marella}})\n|{{sortname|Jim|Ross}}\n|Two-time [[WWWF United States Tag Team Championship|WWWF United States Tag Team Champion]]. Former WWF announcer and onscreen [[Professional wrestling authority figures|President]]<ref name=\"Monsoon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/gorillamonsoon/|title=Gorilla Monsoon|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{sortname|James|Dudley}}\n|{{sortname|Vince|McMahon}}\n|First African American to run a major arena in the United States<ref name=\"Dudley\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/jamesdudley/|title=James Dudley|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-style=\"border-top:2px solid gray;\"\n|}\n\n===Class of 1995===\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name       = WWF Hall of Fame (1995)\n|caption    = \n|image      = \n|alt        =\n|tagline    = \n|theme      = \n|promotion  = [[WWE|WWF]]\n|brand      = \n|date       = {{dts|1995|6|24}}\n|venue      = [[Marriott Hotels & Resorts|Marriott Hotel]]\n|city       = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n|attendance = \n|lastevent  = \n|nextevent  = \n|event      = WWE Hall of Fame\n|lastevent2 = [[WWF Hall of Fame (1994)|1994]]\n|nextevent2 = [[WWF Hall of Fame (1996)|1996]]\n}}\n'''WWF Hall of Fame (1995)''' was the event which featured the introduction of the third class to the WWE Hall of Fame. The event was produced by the [[WWE|WWF]] on June 24, 1995 from the [[Marriott Hotels & Resorts|Marriott Hotel]] in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]. The event took place the same weekend as [[King of the Ring (1995)|King of the Ring]].\n\nIn March 2015 a condensed version of the ceremony was added to the [[WWE Network]].<ref name=networkadd /> Due to the original ceremony only being partially recorded and not originally intended to air, [[Gene Okerlund]] and [[Renee Young]] host the program with added commentary.\n\nThe 1995 class featured two posthumous inductees. [[Antonino Rocca]] was presented by his wife, and [[Ernie Roth|The Grand Wizard]] was represented by Bobby Harmon.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Image\n! Ring name<br />(Birth Name)\n! Inducted by\n! class=\"unsortable\"| WWE recognized accolades\n|-\n|[[File:Antonino Rocca 1956.jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|Antonino|Rocca}}<br />({{small|Antonino Biasetton}})\n|[[Kevin Nash|Diesel]]\n|Posthumous inductee. One-time [[WWF International Heavyweight Championship|WWF International Heavyweight Champion]]. Pioneer of the acrobatic wrestling style<ref name=\"Rocca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/antoninorocca/|title=Antonino Rocca|publisher= [[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Ernie Ladd - Official Wrestling Yearbook No.3, June 1973 Back Cover.jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|\"Big Cat\" Ernie|Ladd|Ernie Ladd}}\n|{{sortname|Bobo|Brazil}}\n|Won several [[National Wrestling Alliance|NWA]] regional titles, and was one of few professional wrestlers to have had a successful career in [[American football]]<ref name=\"Ladd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/ernieladd/|title=\"Big Cat\" Ernie Ladd|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:George Steele.jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|George \"The Animal\"|Steele|George Steele}}<br />({{small|William Myers}})\n|[[Steve Lombardi|Doink the Clown]]\n|One of professional wrestling's first monster [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heels]]<ref name=\"Steele\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/georgesteele/|title=George \"The Animal\" Steele|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Ivan Putski with Paul Billets (cropped).jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|Ivan|Putski}}<br />({{small|J\u00f3zef Bednarski}})\n|{{sortname|Scott|Putski}}\n|One-time [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF Tag Team Champion]]<ref name=\"Putski\">{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/superstars/ivanputski/|title=Ivan Putski|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate= April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:The Fabulous Moolah circa date photograph.jpg|75px]]\n|{{sort|Fabulous Moolah|[[The Fabulous Moolah]]}}<br />({{small|Mary Ellison}})\n|{{sortname|Alundra|Blayze|Madusa}}\n| A four-time [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWF Women's Champion]] prior to her induction, her first reign is recognized as lasting a record 28 years<ref name=\"Moolah\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/fabulousmoolah/|title=The Fabulous Moolah|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{sort|Grand Wizard|[[Ernie Roth|The Grand Wizard]]}}<br />({{small|Irwin Roth}})\n|{{sortname|Sgt.|Slaughter}}\n|Posthumous inductee. <br/> Long-time heel manager in WWF<ref name=\"Wizard\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/thegrandwizard/|title=The Grand Wizard|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Pedro Morales as the WWWF (WWE) Champion.jpg|75px]]\n|{{sortname|Pedro|Morales}}\n|{{sortname|Savio|Vega}}\n|[[Savio Vega]] accepted the induction. One-time [[WWE Championship|WWWF World Heavyweight Champion]] whose reign lasted nearly three years, and the first [[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)|WWF Triple Crown Champion]]<ref name=\"Morales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/pedromorales/|title=Pedro Morales| publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=April 24, 2007}}</ref> He was also the first Latino to win the world title<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.bleacherreport.com/articles/445386-is-john-cena-the-greatest-champion-ever-ranking-all-46-wwe-world-champi#/articles/445386-is-john-cena-the-greatest-champion-ever-ranking-all-46-wwe-world-champi/page/38 |title=John Cena The Greatest Champion Ever? Ranking All 46 WWE World Champions \u221210. Pedro Morales |author=A. Version 2.0 |publisher=BleacherReport.com |date= September 1, 2010 |accessdate=December 23, 2011}}</ref>\n|-style=\"border-top:2px solid gray;\"\n|}\n\n===Class of 1996===\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name       = WWF Hall of Fame (1996)\n|caption    = \n|image      = \n|alt        =\n|tagline    = \n|theme      = \n|promotion  = [[WWE|WWF]]\n|brand      = \n|date       = {{dts|1996|11|16}}\n|venue      = [[New York Marriott Marquis|Marriott Marquis]]\n|city       = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|attendance = \n|lastevent  = \n|nextevent  = \n|event      = WWE Hall of Fame\n|lastevent2 = [[WWF Hall of Fame (1995)|1995]]\n|nextevent2 = [[WWE Hall of Fame (2004)|2004]]\n}}\n'''WWF Hall of Fame (1996)''' was the event which featured the introduction of the fourth class to the WWE Hall of Fame. The event was produced by the [[WWE|WWF]] on November 16, 1996 from the [[New York Marriott Marquis|Marriott Marquis]] in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. The event took place the same weekend as [[Survivor Series (1996)|Survivor Series]].\n\nIn March 2015 a condensed version of the ceremony was added to the [[WWE Network]].<ref name=networkadd /> Due to the original ceremony only being partially recorded and not originally intended to air, [[Gene Okerlund]] and [[Renee Young]] host the program with added commentary.\n\nDue to [[Vincent J. McMahon]]'s passing in 1984, he was posthumously inducted by the [[McMahon family]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Image\n! Ring name<br />(Birth Name)\n! Inducted by\n! class=\"unsortabl